values.QID1_TEXT: Being too shy with the girls
Not finding love in time to be able to have kids before I had lost my ability through hysterectomy.

Believing that it's always psychologically benign to think about any intellectual idea in any situation. 
(including before bed, while listening to friends, while playing basketball, after thinking about it for long enough, etc)
Be more outspoken , mingle with family friends
That I didn't travel or have more fun when I was in my late twenties. I was so focused on achieving at work, getting married, and having kids, that I wouldn't make time to take adventures.
I wish I had been more careful with my body
The way I ended my marriage
not getting my doctorate sooner

Persevering with an extremely unhealthy relationship (where I was all too willing to accept responsibility for us both and she was unwilling to take responsibility for her own wellbeing, and I was unable to deal with this disparity in a healthy way) to the point where I became abusive and was subsequently convicted of three charges relating to domestic abuse. I regret this both in terms of the harm I perpetrated and the consequences for me.
Wasted 2 yrs of my life with someone non committal.  But not to worry I am married and found someone much better.

Not sticking with my original undergraduate college choice and instead ending up at 4 different schools before I graduated. I feel no connection to my alma mater and have no lifelong college friendships.
Anything I have said or when I didn't listen and this hurt someone.  Especially the times I was judgemental and wanted to be right.
Involving myself in a cause with others without any real blood relatives onboard.

Not following God's prompting when considering dating a guy (I did and wish I never had) as well as accepting the job I currently work at. In hindsight, I can see how doing both of these things ended up being the wrong decision. Thankfully, I learned and the 3rd time, listened and obeyed. (I canceled surgery for an issue that seems to be healed.)
Falling in love with someone else when I was married to another person.
Making decisions based on what I TRULY wanted.
Not taking a timeout to spend time with the important people in my life. I have had a tendency to place work responsibilities ahead of my family and others.
Not fully appreciating and enjoying the period of life when my children were young.
NOT leaving my previous job sooner.
Staying in relationships too long
marriage
Letting others tell me who I should be rather than discovering myself out sooner.
Not studying abroad in college
I did not persist at university and in early adulthood with creative writing
That I chose partners whose lives I could make better instead of choosing a partner who would make my life better
Agreed with my spouse to join with spouse's siblings in a family business endeavor. Sibs recently forced us out.

I have let work interfere with my fitness & health... closely followed by spending money on random crap to soothe work stress.... do you sense a theme?  :)
thanks Dan!
That I didn't join the service or go to college.
Not studying abroad in college.
One significant regret I have is not figuring out what my TRUE major in college should have been the first time around...
not finishing my MBA

I wish I would have changed my career a few times while I was still at the entry level stage. I feel like I'm pigeon holed now in my current career, but perhaps I could be a great project manager or salesman.
I wish I would have ventured out to try other things, like the high school musical or golf or tennis or hockey. I think I would have enjoyed them and performed pretty well
Letting someone else take the blame for my wrongdoing
Not visiting my parents/grandparents more when they were alive.

Not spending more time with my grandfather. He was a tough perfectionist however he was also very smart and interesting. I wish I had been braver around him and gotten to know him rather than just popping in and out. He passed away when I was in my early 20s.
Not sleeping more when I was younger and in that vein having a more strict schedule for myself.  I used to stay up very late probably from elementary school on.
Not taking more chances.

I regret being constantly over-committed during my working years, being too busy to spend time at home with my family and generally enjoy life and health. I think it was a way to avoid being responsible for my choices. Now that I'm retired, I'm going slower and enjoying life more, but it is hard to overcome life-long habits.
I didn't learn to speak fluently in another language
Following my heart and not my head!
Not studying abroad while I was in college.
I regret not spending more time playing/practicing the piano and simply allowing it to be a priority in my life.
Not connecting with my grandmother before she passed away. Not getting to know her despite her efforts of trying to get to know me.
Going to (and failing out of) college right out of high school when I didn't want to be in school. Taking out student loans during the time I didn't want to be in college.
Automatically doing what I thought was expected of me, rather than considering what I actually needed to feel happy and fulfilled.
Not spending more time with my near-death mother when she was in the hospital.
I wish I had applied myself more in high school. It may have impacted where I went school, my chosen career, and even where I lived and who I married.
not having kids
I have not saved enough money during my early adult days and it has a significant repercussion on my finances nowadays.
Never found Mr Right
Not spending enough time with my parents when I was in my 30s.
Not investing money when I was younger.
I spent a lot of time getting messed up- smoking weed and drinking too much. I probably could have done less of that and more time pursuing other hobbies.
I regret not learning how to seek help sooner
Not completing my MBA.
Not committing to one thing long enough to master it.
Getting married so young and for the wrong reasons.
Not having more faith in myself.
Having better relationships - with my family and finding that one person to share the rest of your life with.
Getting too drunk on my wedding night

Early in my career (age 22-35), I allowed bad managers to influence how I felt about myself and my work. They held me back from growing and progressing and made me feel that I wasn't measuring up. I wish I had been stronger, bolder, and more confident to stand up to them and call out their terrible management practices, and look for better jobs more quickly instead of staying "for my resume".
Didn’t trust on gut feelings 14 years back and put all myself to execute it..

I accepted a job as an advancement in my career but it involved moving my family and leaving a company I had grown up in.  The new company and area was a mistake for both me and my family and we moved back less than three years later to an area we love but it took an even longer time to get to back to job satisfaction.
I wish I had been more willing to fail; that is, I wish I had been bolder in engaging in situations where I was not likely to succeed, for the sake of learning from the experience.
I majored in Business for a secure job instead of the English I loved.

The one significant regret I have was listening to my high-school guidance teacher who used a graph to illustrate the earnings potential of high school, vs. college, vs. university graduates as a means for me to determine what career I should pursue. I was made to believe that money would be the key driver to my career satisfaction, which as a student who earned minimum wage for 8 hours of work a week seemed a good argument at the time. Anyway, went to university for the typical pre-med courses, instead of college for journalism which I had wanted to do, because he told me I was too smart for college. I spent the next 15 years of my life trying to find a job that I wanted to stay in for more than 1 year. When I found out that this guidance counselor had committed suicide 5 years after I graduated high school several years later, I was even more regretful that I didn't follow my own inner voice. My lesson learned was to ensure that I didn't place my failed dreams or expectations on my son's when choosing a career, and they took their time before pursuing more formal education, and they are content and committed to the choices they made for themselves.
Caring too much what others think of me

You know - the funny thing is that I have always regretted a lot of things in my life - but when I got this question from I gave it som serious thought and now I can´t really say that I really regret anything. Preveously I thought of regretting not getting into the school I then wanted. Saying no to a job offer. 
Now the only thing I can say that I really regret is beeing to harsch on my twin girls when they where kids.

Concentrating on my career for three decades and only realising later in life about starting a family, (in hindsight not a bad thing as would not have found my partner to enjoy being a father with and a focus on enjoying every moment).
Not consistently following my heart over my mind in some career decisions.

Once, as a child, I made an innocently intended remark that I MUCH later realized must have been extremely hurtful to my Mother. I regret that I made the remark, and also that I never found a way to apologize that wouldn't have made things worse by bringing it up.

I regret not going after my PhD the first time through grad school at the "traditional" age.  As a first-generation college student and a female studying Physics in the early 90's, I was intimidated by it.  I earned one later at 41, but the regret remains.
I did not join the military when I was younger. I’m 32 now.
I felt pressured to marry my ex-husband. We should've dated a bit longer before tying the knot.
Not accepting sooner that my depression and anxiety couldn't be cured, but could be adapted to in ways that allowed me to do work I care about and remain close to people I love.

Making a career move to Germany (from Holland) which my gut instinct told me not to do. Rational thinking made me decide to do this. 10 months later I was back in Holland having quit the job. I regret it in the sense that i would not do it again, if I was in the same position. But I don't regret it in learning from my decision making and what I find important in the career vs life balance.
I have never studied  abroad only in Germany. I had the chance but was too shy to go for it.
Not being open to opportunities that came along when I was on my pre-determined path in University. Think outside the box!

Being so afraid of change/the unknown. 
- Moving to a different state, going for that new job - big changes I was initially horrified of because I didn't know how they would turn out, but none of them were near as big a deal (or as terrible) as I made them out to be.
I should have had therapy sooner
Being passive for far too long.  Embrace the fear and move on.
I didn't take my wife's mental health issues more seriously before we had children.

My biggest regret is screwing up my life to the point that I had to give up my kids. They've been living with my parents for 12 years now. After all the screwing up, my health decided to get interesting, so I haven't even been able to visit them in 3 or 4 years. I talk to my daughter every Sunday afternoon. I've talked to my son once in the last two and a half years; he's in a therapeutic boarding school after a suicide attempt. I look back and wonder where everything went wrong.
That I didn't go to film school.

One of my biggest regrets in life was staying in a relationship longer than I should have. It was the kind of relationship you know is toxic and leading nowhere, but you stay out of fear of being alone. My partner needed me more than I needed them, we both knew it, but we stayed together because I was scared I wouldn't find someone else who would love me. I found that it was more damaging to stay in the relationship for a variety of different reasons. Some of those reasons included: my partner was financially draining, and psychological damage. The day I ended our relationship was the best decision I ever made for myself. I felt bad, and still do to this day, and the only thing I regret is leading this person on and not ending things sooner.
Not valuing myself soon enough - not doing as well as I could have in school (to fit in) which impacted everything and settling for the wrong relationships.
I wish I had started my 401k straight out of school.

I wish I had spent more time with my grandmother before she died. In the end, she wanted the freedom of death and that was such a scary and sad thing to me that I ran away from it and avoided her. I regret that I didn't have the courage to accept her where she was and be a companion anyway.

Two regrets: 

I regret not taking academics more seriously in college. I have a great career and make great money compared to others, but I could have made more opportunities for myself.

Regret not asking for help early in my career. People want to help you. I did not learn to ask for help until I had a few painful professional experiences. I've learned from them :-)
Not quitting that job sooner
Not taking more risks earlier in life - exploring the world, meeting more people, following my heart into adventures that didn't "fit the box".

I am not being glib but I do not have a significant regret. I have not had a perfect ride but I am happy with my outcomes and my relationships. I have many things I could have improved on in a do-over but I hope I learned something from them! The thing I have said to friends is that I guess when I took the "path less traveled by" I actually could have / would have enjoyed taking BOTH paths. There is so much to see and do. But you choose, and play the hand you are dealt, right?  Enjoy every sandwich as Warren Zevon said.
That I didn't get out of a marriage that wasn't making me happy sooner. I was afraid to let go and be alone.
Staying in a job for too long - just waiting for that progression or moment of opportunity that never came.

It's difficult to regret something because I know everything led me to where I am now. For example, I might regret that I was so inconsiderate while making plans to travel around the world, resulting in my boyfriend breaking up with me. But then I might not ever have moved to South Korea, and I believe I would have regretted never fulfilling a dream to live abroad. 
I guess my biggest regret would be stressing over things that already happened and getting upset/anxious. Feeling bad about choices I already made. It doesn't feel good, and it doesn't help. It’s a waste of time and energy, and it distracts from enjoying the present moment. Better to look at the experience with love and forgiveness, and figure out if there's anything to be learned.

I regret not having focused my career on one rather obscure topic that I was passionate about and could become a serious expert in over 30 years such that I could feel my expertise is really valuable at the end of my career and would give me as sense of being in demand even as I pass traditional retirement age.
Making a decision based on what I thought other people might think, instead of basing it on my own feelings.
I regret not being more confident and comfortable with myself so i could dress the way i wanted and do the things i wanted to do.
Not taking more chances / being bolder

My biggest regret is succumbing to my lack of confidence and emotional instability in college. I didn't seek the right kind of help and it made for a miserable four years. It could have been SO DIFFERENT and I could have taken a much different career path that was  more fulfilling much sooner in my life.
I have made many mistakes, but I like who I am now and don’t know that would be true if I made changes.
Not joining the military. I could have served my country more in a life of active service. I finally came to government service and love my work. I wish I'd started earlier.
I wish I had been more adventurous when I was a young adult, and been more confident - maybe traveled or studied abroad.
Not daring greatly.  Didn't know what that meant until later in life.  So not really a regret since it is hindsight, but more of an observation.
Not going 'away' to college. i was a commuter and worked full-time from freshman year of college all the way through grad school. i would i could have taken time to just be a student.
Closing my relationship (with a significant other) window to focus on career. I thought it would distract me from my goals at the time.
Taking bigger career risks. Fear of failure was holding me back.

I regret getting into personal debt early in life for frivolous and wasteful purchases that meant nothing because I then had to use a chunk of my 401K investment to remove that burden when I could have been spending those youthful years more charitably or traveling to see the world.  It was an important lesson to learn that has shaped my future, but I regret the economic and material waste as well as the wasted years where I was handcuffed by that debt.

I have always been a supporter of LGBTQ causes and the community, but for many years my support was as closeted as were many of my colleagues (I am a cisgender straight white guy).  So I was at an event where my "power" as an senior executive was in play, and I was asked about my position on gay marriage.  I hedged and hemmed and hawed and ended up spitting out some lukewarm response about "contracts" vs embracing a full endorsement.  I edited myself, in other words, and lied about what I truly believed and felt.  I immediately experienced regret and palpably felt the disappointment many in the room felt about what I'd said, people who privately knew what I really believed.  It was a moment in which I felt a betrayal of myself and a violation of one of my core values (Authenticity).  
I have never since that event failed to respond fully when people ask my personal position on any issue. I own what I believe and accept that because of my privilege and rank that my voicing support for minority positions really matters, both for the minority group (women, people of color, LGBTQ, especially) and for the influence I can have on conversations in the larger community

Not insisting my education was as valuable as my (ex) husband's. It put my start in college back two decades. I wish I'd learned earlier that I could have made it a requirement of the marriage, because so much else important turned out to be related to valuing my education.
Spending too much time on homework/work and not enough with friends and family
I wish I would have studied abroad in college

Not overcoming my fear of public speaking earlier. I waited 30 years.
By the way, my name is Derek Deprey. Thank you for tweeting my book, SHIFT: Move from Frustrated to Fulfilled a couple of years ago. Meant the world to me. I'm working on a new book called, Rise Above Robo-Bosses: How to Thrive as a Leader in the Digital Era. I'd be honored to be on a Pinkcast. 
Either way, thank you adding value to my life. You are amazing.
Derek Deprey 414.803.2491 or derek@derekdeprey.com
That I do not have a partner to share my life with.  I am twice divorced and did not try hard enough to find someone new.
Carolyn T - backing out of a relationship with her

I wish I had been there for a friend when her grandma died. Not necessarily saying or doing anything, just sitting with her and being there. 
I wish I had used my college summers more effectively - applied to internships, taken summer school, studied abroad, or even worked a wait staff job - anything beyond chilling at home.
Breaking up badly with a very sweet boyfriend.  I was a jerk.  It's the first thing that popped into my head and the speed with which it popped up emphasized its impact.
I wish that I had taken more chances academically and professionally.

That I didn't keep contact info for more of the people I met along the way. I didn't read that Bill Clinton kept 3X5 index cards for everyone he met (and look where that got him) until it was too late. And I wish I hadn't gotten married when I got out of the army, moved to Key West and worked as a bartender until I sold my first novel!
Being brought up in the UK
Letting the fear or rejection keep me from becoming an occupational therapist.
Taking romantic relationships too seriously and not just enjoying the other's presence and the positive emotions they evoked.
I regret not speaking up more in my marriage when things were going south.
I didn't study abroad in college
I regret not having pursued getting a Master's and PhD before having a family.  I thought I was too busy with my career, I had no idea.
So long time at university being so young

I wish I'd spent more time making lasting friendships and focusing on my art (music), instead of being perfectionistic about my grades and assignments in junior high and high school.  Teachers were all too ready to encourage this "star student" attitude that kept me judgmental of others and from having any close friends until college.  Instead of learning to empathize with others, playing and making memories, I spent my time worrying about the best way to phrase my sentences, what a waste of childhood.
I regret not having a frank discussion with my husband prior to marriage about having children.
Too much self-doubt
I took my mom for granted.  Then, she died.
Missing my sons appointment to school captain of his grade school for work
I wish I’d had more children

Thinking I had to get a "real job" right out of college & marriage - we had to prove to our parents we were grown up.  I wish we had taken chances - explored more travel etc   before we settled down with jobs and started our family.

I regret that I was not introduced to EST or the work of Landmark earlier in my life. My lack of awareness of what I have learned since participating at age 39 certainly impacted my choices and what I could perceive as possible for myself and others prior to that time. I paid a large opportunity cost by missing this training earlier in my life. I have a great, extraordinary life now. All is well.

I wish I had been bolder when I had to choose my high school.
I could have chosen to study arts (I was very good at it as a kid), but I let myself be dragged to a scientific/linguistic high school.
While I'm happy with my life today, I still dream of a parallel universe, where my other self is a graphic novel artist.
Working too hard and investing too much time in training.
I regret not learning how to listen.
Not working earlier in my life to be comfortable with who I am

Not changing my mind.  At 22, I accepted a job in Washington DC, which started in 3 months.  Within weeks of accepting, I realized I didn't want to leave California.  I felt guilty at the thought of backing out.  They had lots of other interested candidates and would've found someone.  But I thought, "well, it's just a 1 year contract... I can survive 1 year."  I ended up suffering from a life changing injury while on that job.  I regret not listening to my gut, because the injury altered the course of my life.  I have grown a lot as a result of this situation, so it's not that nothing has come from it.  But I think I could've learned these lessons in a less painful manner...  And I regret not listening to my gut and sticking to what was right for me, and just managing the discomfort of any fall out.
Not pursuing a medical career.
Not managing my income better and not saving more when I was young.

That I listened to people when I was looking for an easy out; and followed their counsel even when I knew it wasn’t the right thing to do. I guess with age you know the answer is always inside you; you learn the lesson of how to get it out

1. Being so afraid of what other's think, so as to compromise myself and potential relationships.

1.2. (Also--not standing up to my doctor when I felt my health was off--so wasting a decade on getting a proper diagnosis and treatment.)

1.3. ((Also--not pursuing my genuine interests sooner.))
I regret making decisions (regarding relationships, college classes I took, among other things) out of fear.
Not being bolder and experimenting more with creativity.
I wish I'd been more honest with people and less afraid of challenging the status quo, both professionally and personally.

I regret two things: 
1. Not knowing how to really sink my teeth into studies & research. I studied to test & I got good grades. Next. I wish I had better focus & could get into research & study more.
2. I am now a kind person. Regretfully, this was not always the case. I am proud now to know the difference: kindness is better.
I regret getting married so young - the first time. (I subsequently divorced and remarried).
Not starting my own business
Focusing on grades and having fun in college, going on summer schools abroad and such, instead of thinking of my future and going for internships and the potential jobs I could've gotten from them.
Believing the world lives by my standards.
Not dealing with my eating disorder sooner.
Nothing. I've learned from every decision I've ever made. And while not perfect, or even what I had planned, my life has turned out better than I could have imagined in – almost – every way.
Abandoning good friends
Trying to be perfect!

Is not have studied the career I wanted, the most important and significan regret I have.

Or some of the careers ... my grandmother, always find an important inconvenience in them, then I studied what she wanted.
Doing the hard psychological work earlier in my life (rather than waiting until my forties) to support more success and joy later in my life.
Decision-making focused on fear and failure rather than courage and growth.

I regret not taking the time and effort to plan out a career path before choosing a major (and minor) in college. My current career has nothing to do with either and I'm constantly wondering if I should go back to university to start over in something I am actually passionate about or stick with the safe paycheck to be sure my family is taken care of.
Gaining weight, a few pounds a year, through my life.

I wish I had 'sold' myself better when talking to Coach Jerry Kindall about walking on to the University of Arizona baseball team as a freshman. I was intimidated by him being the author of the Sports Illustrated book on baseball in the library. I only answered his direct questions; "yes, sir", " no, sir". I should have told him I already had an AF ROTC scholarship and simply wanted to be a defensive replacement as I was a better defensive outfielder than his starters the previous year. In hindsight, however, graduating with a Math degree was hard enough. Maybe it was a good thing I didn't try to add another commitment.
Not being more bold, not caring what others think.... Going for it!
Be straightforward (yet still kind) with my feelings.
Being concerned about what others think of me.
No savings
I wish I had not had a boyfriend through college who monopolized my time and I had met more great people.  I went to an amazing university!!
I did not take financial risks that would have made me more money when I could afford to take the risk (i.e., invest in real estate). I played it safe and now I am still scraping by.

That I didn't travel abroad sooner, in college or in my 20s. I would have learned so much more about the world. Other than that, things are just mistakes or lessons learned, not regrets. Life's too short to look backwards too much.
Wish I would have committed to my now wife earlier. Life has been so much better since.

Being over critical both on myself and others.  I set the bar very high and expected everyone to live/be at that level. I was very judgmental of those that didn't meet high standards. And looking back, many people did achieve great things in their own time.
I regret that I retired when I did. I have so much more to offer and I don't always have a way to engage.

Not listening to a strong internal voice regarding the fit between my (now former) wife and I. While, the union did result in my beautiful and valued daughter, many good memories, and a toolbox of learning. Though ultimately, with the exception of my daughter, I probably would have discovered, learned, and experienced a better 22 years if I focused on growing myself and my partner in place of trying to fit expectations that I just could not fulfill. 

That said it's regret, not a permanent situation. I now focus on being me, learning from the experiences of the past, and discovering new options and opportunities.
Being timid when I should have been brave (deciding NOT to get married at about age 25), and being bold and arrogant when I should have been cautious (deciding TO get married at age 32).
I wish I would have listened to my instincts more often instead of over ruling them to be "nice".
That I didn't go to a more prestigious university (Smith College) when I had the chance.
Marrying my ex husband
Not editing my senior thesis on Philip Jaisohn for publication when his memorial organisation asked me to. I was 21 and just too lazy. No other good reason.
I regret slamming my brother's fingers in a door in a fit of (immature, show-off-for-effect) rage during college.  Ironically, I've since apologized and he doesn't even remember it.
After marriage and before the blessings of children arrived, my spouse and I should have traveled more.
When younger, making decisions based on someone else's fear
Drinking so much alcohol in college and going to law school.
Not being focused on the things that truly matter in life in my 20s.

Fear of rejection held me back from many potential relationships. It still does... but I'm working on it. I wonder how many friendships I've missed out on because I assumed other people would not like me.

I regret not finishing college when I was young.  I tried to take classes while working full-time jobs, but the jobs demanded too many hours (frequently 80+ hours a week).  I returned to college full-time last year with every intention of completing this degree.  It is painful; however, only eight classes remaining!
Lacking the courage or energy to speak up or do the right thing in a difficult situation.
I wish i had been able to stay home longer when my boys were little.
Getting pregnant at 21/unmarried

Procrastinating things I wanted to do until the time was better. Waiting to travel, to write, to do things I figured I'd eventually do- until I had more money, was older, was wiser, liked myself more. Basically living like I had all the time in the world. There will never be a perfect time to do some things

Not working on the important work, instead doing all the busy work, the scrolling, the emails, the dishes, the tidying, the mundane, anything but the deep, hard, meaningful work that I want to do in life.

I regret not travelling enough and more often while married, alone with each one, and all together as group, with my four kids (Mike age 43, Ilana age 40, Julia age 18 and David age 14) in order to dive into their private dreams and fullfillments.  Anyway I am their proud father and still get inspired by them.
Not having another child

Settling for what I thought was "the best I could get", in terms of a not so great partner. That one wrong choice led to other not so great choices in terms of career advancement, becoming a single parent, etc. Its crazy but true... pick a partner that brings you up, or opt to be alone. Don't settle.

Spending my working year in the corporate world with the blatant discrimination against and abuse of women in the workplace, as well as the gender pay which reduced my benefits.  Also, I regret believing that the corporate powers could not cheat us on the retirement plan.  I should not have gotten business degrees, but should have pursued a different path.
I wasn't brave in my choices, so I didn't seek out new experiences.
I wish i'd been bolder and quicker in recognising and making changes when things weren't working for me - either at work or in my personal life.
Not pursuing a dual-degree program while in graduate school
As a young adult not asking my parents more about their lives, advice, etc., before they died. (They were both dead by the time I was 33.)
Marrying my husband
Taking few risks at an early age while stakes were low. Career, relationship, etc.
